have got to be careful about
saying that we

28:28.574 --> 28:30.976 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
had all the answers during the
Obama administration.

28:31.009 --> 28:33.145 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think Colin would agree with
that.

28:33.178 --> 28:36.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This president's going find a
decision-making
process that works for him.

28:36.949 --> 28:42.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What happened in Yemen may cause
him to rethink
the way in which he approved
this raid, because

28:42.421 --> 28:44.323 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
you can always delegate
authority.

28:44.356 --> 28:46.024 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You can never delegate the risk.

28:46.058 --> 28:49.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ultimately, you're going to own
that, as Dr.
Gorka mentioned from the White
House.

28:50.028 --> 28:53.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Andrew, I want
to -- you
recently wrote that blaming the
president

28:53.599 --> 28:56.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is both inappropriate and
counterproductive.

28:56.902 --> 29:01.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You also described sometimes
that the process
can be paralysis by analysis.

29:01.373 --> 29:02.541 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANDREW EXUM: Yes.

29:02.574 --> 29:03.442 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That it can
take a very
long time.

29:03.475 --> 29:05.177 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANDREW EXUM: No, that's right.

29:05.210 --> 29:09.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Colin remembers that, at one
point in the
waning days of the Obama
administration, I

29:09.548 --> 29:14.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think we were debating at the
Cabinet level
the movement of three
helicopters from Iraq

29:14.987 --> 29:16.788 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to Syria.

29:16.822 --> 29:20.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, there are obvious, you
know, political
implications of anything you do
on the ground.

29:20.993 --> 29:24.830 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But at what point do you
delegate authority
down to your commander on the
ground, I think,

29:24.863 --> 29:26.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is the key question.

29:26.698 --> 29:30.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The reason why I think putting
the -- putting
real blame on the Trump
administration here

29:30.802 --> 29:33.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is dangerous is because you have
the Benghazi
effect.

29:33.672 --> 29:38.310 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
You remember, when the
Republicans used Benghazi
and what happened there as a
cudgel to beat

29:38.343 --> 29:43.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hillary Clinton, and without --
you know their
effort was successful, it must
be added, to

29:43.048 --> 29:44.816 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
weaken her as a political
candidate.

29:44.850 --> 29:47.386 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But it also had a chilling
effect on the bureaucracy.

29:47.419 --> 29:49.054 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It makes the bureaucracy
risk-averse.

29:49.087 --> 29:52.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, quite frankly, that's not
something that
we want from our diplomats.

29:52.257 --> 29:54.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not something we want from
our special
operators.

29:54.926 --> 29:56.061 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We want them to be aggressive.

29:56.094 --> 29:57.896 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We want them to take risks.

29:57.929 --> 30:02.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when we elevate the blame,
when something
goes wrong, all the way to the
presidential

30:02.401 --> 30:05.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
level, we just have got to be
very careful
about how we do that.

30:05.137 --> 30:08.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And, Colin,
why does it
take so long?

30:08.473 --> 30:11.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What kinds of input factor into
a decision
like this?

30:11.176 --> 30:14.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
®MD-BO /COLIN KAHL: Yes, look, I
think that
the Obama administration can be
criticized

30:14.146 --> 30:16.415 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for too much micromanagement of
the Pentagon.

30:16.448 --> 30:21.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, you know, the question
is, did they
swing the pendulum too far in
one direction?

30:21.253 --> 30:25.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I worry that President
Trump, in the first
big decision that came to his,
in this case,

30:26.024 --> 30:30.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dinner table as commander in
chief, he swung
the pendulum all the way back in
the other

30:30.562 --> 30:32.297 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
direction.

30:32.330 --> 30:34.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Look, what President Obama
insisted on is,
every time that the military
wanted to come

30:34.566 --> 30:39.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
forward to ask for authority to
significantly
escalate, especially to put
ground forces

30:39.805 --> 30:44.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into a conflict environment,
where people
can die, both our service
members, but also

30:44.376 --> 30:48.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
civilians and others, that we
needed to have
a careful, deliberate process.

30:48.814 --> 30:50.215 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It doesn't have to take weeks.

30:50.248 --> 30:52.117 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It oftentimes takes a couple of
days.

30:52.150 --> 30:55.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it works its way through,
and you get
the inputs from all the various
agencies.

30:55.687 --> 31:00.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question I have with Trump's
decision-making
process here is not that you
have to do it

31:00.492 --> 31:03.862 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
exactly the way we did it, but
he didn't run
a process at all.

31:03.895 --> 31:08.767 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He just had dinner with
Secretary Mattis and
General Dunford and a handful of
close advisers

31:08.800 --> 31:11.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and was briefed about the raid
and made a
decision.

31:11.436 --> 31:15.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as a consequence, he didn't
have the
full benefit of his intelligence
professionals,

31:15.774 --> 31:17.242 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of his State Department.

31:17.275 --> 31:20.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that is a recipe for making
mistakes and
costing people their lives.

31:20.479 --> 31:25.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Andrew Exum,
what about
the idea that, when there are
these different

31:25.117 --> 31:28.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
agencies, these different people
weighing
in on it, that they're going to
think about

31:28.353 --> 31:33.658 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
diplomatic consequences,
political consequences,
things that perhaps a commander
in the field

31:33.692 --> 31:38.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
might not think about because,
for him or
her, they see a much different
objective?

31:38.096 --> 31:39.898 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANDREW EXUM: Yes, it's a valid
point.

31:39.931 --> 31:43.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the way Colin described
things, I
think he's right that the
pendulum swung back.

31:43.702 --> 31:47.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I wouldn't say it went all the
way back, because,
again, the decision-making
process in this

31:47.405 --> 31:51.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
