very rigorous
process in the Pentagon.

31:51.042 --> 31:54.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It would have been blessed off
by all the
Pentagon senior leaders before
it would have

31:54.479 --> 31:55.947 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
been presented to the president.

31:55.981 --> 31:58.116 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So it wasn't completely without
rigor.

31:58.150 --> 32:03.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think what Colin is
describing in terms
of baking down the risk, that
does happen

32:03.722 --> 32:05.757 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in a deliberate process like
that.

32:05.791 --> 32:07.559 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The key question is opportunity
cost.

32:07.592 --> 32:11.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in the Obama administration,
we had a
very deliberate process that in
many cases

32:11.763 --> 32:14.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
served the president and was
what the president
desired.

32:14.900 --> 32:20.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It drew down a lot of political
risks, as
well as the physical risk, to
the operators

32:20.205 --> 32:21.306 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on the ground.

32:21.339 --> 32:23.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The question is, was there an
opportunity
cost?

32:23.475 --> 32:26.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The nature of these raids is,
they go after
time-sensitive targets.

32:26.812 --> 32:31.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So do you lose opportunities the
more that
you hold things up in
Washington?

32:31.983 --> 32:33.785 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think that's the key question.

32:33.819 --> 32:37.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And where Colin and I may
disagree, but where
I think we do agree, is that
there has to

32:37.989 --> 32:39.090 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be a balance.

32:39.124 --> 32:41.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just a matter of where you
strike that
balance.

32:41.259 --> 32:53.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Andrew Exum,
Colin Kahl, thank you both.

32:53.405 --> 32:56.441 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

