35:39.004 --> 35:40.939 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: I have used it four times.

35:40.972 --> 35:42.374 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I keep them in my bag.

35:42.407 --> 35:44.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I always keep them in my bag, at
least four
or five of them in my bag.

35:44.342 --> 35:46.511 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN HARRIS, Baltimore Health
Department:
This is our mobile unit.

35:46.544 --> 35:50.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: John Harris
works on one
of the Health Department's vans
which traverse

35:50.281 --> 35:56.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the city offering sexually
transmitted infection
screenings, clean needle kits
and naloxone

35:56.154 --> 35:57.989 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
training.

35:58.023 --> 36:01.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN HARRIS: Well, we tell
people that, once
you reverse an overdose, then
not to use that.

36:01.593 --> 36:06.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: He knows what
addiction can
do to a person, having spent 16
years addicted

36:06.865 --> 36:08.099 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to heroin.

36:08.133 --> 36:09.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But he sees something different
today.

36:09.901 --> 36:14.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN HARRIS: There was a lot of
fentanyl at
first that we were hearing
about.

36:14.406 --> 36:21.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But now the clients are starting
to come with
medications that they use on an
elephant,

36:21.513 --> 36:24.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tranquilizers being cut with
heroin.

36:24.482 --> 36:26.317 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There are benzodiazepines.

36:26.351 --> 36:29.554 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We're hearing about all
different types of
drugs.

36:29.587 --> 36:31.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's really becoming more
complicated and
dangerous.

36:31.990 --> 36:37.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: Since January
2015, the Baltimore
Health Department says over
20,000 residents

36:37.829 --> 36:42.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have completed naloxone training
and at least
800 lives have been saved.

36:42.767 --> 36:47.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And many more states and
municipalities across
the country have moved to make
naloxone more

36:47.839 --> 36:49.774 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
accessible to the public.

36:49.808 --> 36:52.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But not everyone believes this
is the right
approach.

36:52.210 --> 36:56.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE GIMBEL, Maryland Addiction
Recovery Center:
We are selling it to the public
as if it's

36:56.114 --> 36:57.882 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the answer.

36:57.916 --> 37:03.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, it's an amazing drug, no
doubt about
it, but it doesn't change the
behavior of

37:03.321 --> 37:05.090 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the addict.

37:05.123 --> 37:08.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: For 25 years,
Mike Gimbel
was Baltimore County's director
of substance

37:08.626 --> 37:10.462 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
abuse.

37:10.495 --> 37:14.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now he's a consultant for
Maryland Addiction
Recovery Center, a private
treatment facility

37:14.933 --> 37:16.101 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
outside the city.

37:16.134 --> 37:19.204 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And like John Harris, Gimbel is
in recovery.

37:19.237 --> 37:22.073 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE GIMBEL: Heroin is the
devil.

37:22.107 --> 37:23.741 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's the devil.

37:23.775 --> 37:27.645 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It makes you do things you would
never do
you in your life.

37:27.679 --> 37:33.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It took a middle-class, good
Jewish kid like
me, and had me robing my own
parents, carrying

37:33.718 --> 37:35.186 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a gun.

37:35.220 --> 37:36.454 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's what heroin does.

37:36.488 --> 37:38.256 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's how powerful heroin is.

37:38.289 --> 37:42.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: He argues that
the city and
state are spending too much time
and money

37:42.460 --> 37:47.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on Narcan training and outreach,
and not enough
on long-term recovery.

37:47.298 --> 37:52.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And as a sign this approach
isn't working,
he points to the city's rising
overdose fatalities,

37:52.570 --> 37:59.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up 68 percent for the first
three-quarters
of 2016 over the same period the
year before.

37:59.177 --> 38:07.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE GIMBEL: Sometimes, by
having Narcan so
available, it actually
reinforces the addict's

38:07.585 --> 38:09.220 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
behavior.

38:09.254 --> 38:15.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Why should I stop using heroin,
when, if I
overdose, Narcan's going to save
my life?

38:15.493 --> 38:18.596 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Where's the motivation to stop?

38:18.630 --> 38:20.598 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's not there.

38:20.632 --> 38:22.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's not there.

38:22.467 --> 38:26.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, sometimes, yes -- and we
don't want to
see people die, but, sometimes,
watching someone

38:26.704 --> 38:31.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
die and watching what happens
with overdose
and death wakes up a lot of
addicts.

38:31.342 --> 38:32.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIMMY HALL, Former Baltimore
Police Officer:
It's just a first-responder
tool.

38:32.977 --> 38:34.946 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's all it is.

38:34.979 --> 38:38.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: Timmy Hall was
with the Baltimore
Police Department for 24 years,
where he routinely

38:38.983 --> 38:41.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
saw opioid overdoses.

38:41.119 --> 38:46.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He says officers often use
Narcan to revive
the same drug users over and
over again.

38:46.758 --> 38:51.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIMMY HALL: A lot of times, they
get upset
with you when you bring them
back, because

38:51.529 --> 38:53.698 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they feel like you wasted the
money they spent.

38:53.731 --> 38:55.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, that's the feeling
that they wanted.

38:55.733 --> 38:57.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That wanted that feeling, and
you took it
away from them.

38:57.902 --> 38:59.938 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: But Hall
doesn't see an alternative.

38:59.971 --> 39:04.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIMMY HALL: As a police officer,
your first
job is to protect and serve, you
know?

39:04.609 --> 39:07.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what officer would want to
sit there and
watch somebody die, if they got
the tools

39:07.845 --> 39:08.813 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to save somebody?

39:08.846 --> 39:10.448 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, Narcan, to me, is a great
tool.

39:10.481 --> 39:12.417 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's just a first-responder
tool.

39:12.450 --> 39:17.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: The Health
Department attributes
the continued rise in overdoses
and fatalities

39:17.055 --> 39:20.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to a rise in far more powerful
drugs hitting
the streets.

39:20.825 --> 39:26.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Wen says there's no evidence
that denying
naloxone to overdose victims
helps users end

39:26.331 --> 39:28.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
their addictions.

39:28.266 --> 39:30.401 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Naloxone is just one tool in
this fight.

39:30.435 --> 39:32.170 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

39:32.203 --> 39:34.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEANA WEN: We are just treading
water if all
we're doing is saving someone's
life right

39:34.305 --> 39:35.940 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

39:35.974 --> 39:39.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We also know that we have to get
them the
second part, which is access to
long-term

39:39.244 --> 39:44.282 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
treatments, that it's a
combination of medications
and some treatments,
psychosocial treatments,

39:44.315 --> 39:45.650 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like counseling.

39:45.683 --> 39:48.486 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then other services are
important too,
including housing.

39:48.519 --> 39:52.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: Of course,
those all cost
money and political will.

39:52.323 --> 39:54.158 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

39:54.192 --> 39:58.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LARRY HOGAN (R), Maryland:
Heroin and opioid
abuse has been taking lives and
tearing apart

39:58.162 --> 40:00.031 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
families.

40:00.064 --> 40:03.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: Just today,
Maryland's Republican
governor, Larry Hogan, announced
a state of

40:03.101 --> 40:08.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
emergency to deal with the
crisis, pledging
50 million additional dollars
over five years

40:08.873 --> 40:11.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for enforcement, treatment and
prevention.

40:11.709 --> 40:14.045 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN HARRIS: It's got to get
better.

40:14.078 --> 40:15.046 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's got to get better.

40:15.079 --> 40:16.814 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I believe it will get
better.

40:16.848 --> 40:22.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think perfection exists
in anything,
but I do believe Baltimore has
done a lot

40:22.920 --> 40:27.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of good work, will do some more
good work,
because we are saving lives.

40:27.358 --> 40:31.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAMELA KIRKLAND: Saving some
lives amid a
growing epidemic.

40:31.429 --> 40:38.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Pamela Kirkland
in Baltimore.

40:38.102 --> 40:52.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now: two
high-flying companies
whose value has soared and are
the subject

40:52.784 --> 40:56.688 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of intense scrutiny, Uber, and
the parent
company of Snapchat.

40:56.721 --> 41:01.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For Uber, it's about the culture
and leadership
of the ride-hailing service,
valued at nearly

41:01.592 --> 41:03.428 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
$70 billion.

41:03.461 --> 41:07.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's back in the spotlight
following release
of a video of its CEO berating
an Uber driver.

41:07.999 --> 41:09.634 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
More on that in a moment.

41:09.667 --> 41:12.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first, Snapchat is about to
sell its
stock to the public for the
first time.

41:12.937 --> 41:17.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The parent company announced it
will offer
its share at $17 a share,
bringing its value

41:18.009 --> 41:20.678 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to nearly $24 billion.

41:20.712 --> 41:25.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The messaging app is used by
nearly 160 million
people each day, and is
especially popular

41:25.683 --> 41:27.618 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
among teens and young adults.

41:27.652 --> 41:31.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there are big questions
about whether
it's worth this kind of value.

41:31.756 --> 41:34.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mike Isaac is covering both
these stories
for The New York Times.

41:34.158 --> 41:35.126 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He joins me now.

41:35.159 --> 41:36.427 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Let's start with Snapchat.

41:36.461 --> 41:39.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is the value that Snapchat
is trying
to sell investors?

41:39.063 --> 41:41.065 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE ISAAC, The New York Times:
Yes.

41:41.099 --> 41:46.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Snapchat's big story is,
it's going to
be its next Facebook and not the
next Twitter,

41:46.471 --> 41:48.272 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
essentially.

41:48.306 --> 41:52.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of Twitter's big struggles,
if you remember,
when it went public a few years
ago, is, it

41:52.210 --> 41:57.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sort of failed to grow fast
enough for investors
on Wall Street.

41:57.348 --> 42:02.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, as far as Facebook is
concerned, their
growth was huge, but Snapchat
just wants to

42:02.387 --> 42:04.622 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
say, like, look, this is the
next big social
network.

42:04.655 --> 42:09.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You want to get in as quickly as
possible
on the ground floor of this IPO,
and we're

42:09.660 --> 42:15.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to have the success and
strength and
reach of Facebook, particularly
with younger

42:15.166 --> 42:16.267 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
users.

42:16.300 --> 42:17.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How does it
plan to make
money?

42:17.435 --> 42:20.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At one point, it calls itself
now a camera
company.

42:20.271 --> 42:21.339 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, is it a social network?

42:21.372 --> 42:22.573 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is it a camera company?

42:22.607 --> 42:24.275 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do they make money selling
advertisements?

42:24.308 --> 42:28.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MIKE ISAAC: Yes, so it's
primarily advertisements.

42:28.246 --> 42:32.517 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have little what they call
Snapchat stories.

42:32.550 --> 42:39.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And publications like The New
York Times will
show different things inside of
their -- usually

42:39.290 --> 42:40.258 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
video and photo-based.

42:40.291 --> 42:42.827 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then they sell ads against
that.

42:42.860 --> 42:46.564 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then they're kind of
experimenting with
other things, whether it's like
e-commerce-related

42:46.597 --> 42:48.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
things inside the app.

42:48.699 --> 42:50.501 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And then who knows?

42:50.535 --> 42:54.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have what are called
Snapchat Spectacles,
which are glasses on your face,
and maybe

42:54.705 --> 42:55.740 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they can make money from that.

42:55.773 --> 42:57.475 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm not really sure.

42:57.508 --> 42:59.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And so part of
the reason
that it looks like Wall Street
is excited

42:59.444 --> 43:01.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is because there hasn't been a
big tech IPO
in a while.

43:01.779 --> 43:03.648 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MIKE ISAAC: Yes, that's right.

43:03.681 --> 43:10.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think a lot of investors feel
like they
missed out on Facebook a few
years ago, especially

43:10.688 --> 43:14.826 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
when the IPO went really
terribly for the
company, and now Facebook is
trading at over

43:14.859 --> 43:17.228 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
$100 a share.

43:17.261 --> 43:21.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I think everyone is really
looking forward
to a successful IPO from a tech
company.

43:21.365 --> 43:23.201 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it has been a bit.

43:23.234 --> 43:26.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And these two
founders have
also decided to take a lot of
the -- I guess

43:26.838 --> 43:28.639 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the voting control of the
company.

43:28.673 --> 43:30.074 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This seems to be the new thing.

43:30.107 --> 43:33.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mark Zuckerberg has a tremendous
amount of
control over his company.

43:33.411 --> 43:35.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is this the kind of template
that now tech
CEOs want?

43:35.646 --> 43:37.415 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MIKE ISAAC: I think so.

43:37.448 --> 43:44.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think investors kind of
have a sense
of trust that the founders tend
to know best

43:44.188 --> 43:46.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
