TRAVIS KALANICK: Some people
don't like to
take responsibility for their...

44:42.146 --> 44:43.614 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

44:43.648 --> 44:47.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TRAVIS KALANICK: They blame
everything in
their life on somebody else.

44:47.218 --> 44:48.185 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

44:48.219 --> 44:49.520 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TRAVIS KALANICK: Good luck.

44:49.554 --> 44:52.356 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: Good luck to you, too.

44:52.390 --> 44:54.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Kalanick later
apologized.

44:54.725 --> 44:59.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said in a statement: "It's
clear this video
is a reflection of me, and the
criticism we

44:59.997 --> 45:05.703 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
have received is a stark
reminder that I must
fundamentally change as a leader
and grow

45:05.736 --> 45:06.704 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up."

45:06.737 --> 45:08.205 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's part of the statement.

45:08.239 --> 45:12.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Mike, why is this apology to
the driver
and the company so important?

45:12.543 --> 45:17.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE ISAAC: If you followed the
company for
the past seven years, one thing
you can say

45:17.949 --> 45:21.919 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about Travis Kalanick, he's
pretty unapologetic.

45:21.953 --> 45:23.888 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He's aggressive.

45:23.921 --> 45:28.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's pushed into markets where
operating Uber
was actually illegal.

45:28.292 --> 45:33.230 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And it's been a real
no-holds-barred approach
to operating a company.

45:33.264 --> 45:38.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, to see him say, I have to be
humble, I
have to change the type of
leader that I am

45:38.069 --> 45:39.470 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is a real big shift for them.

45:39.503 --> 45:42.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm really curious if he can
actually
do it at this point.

45:42.640 --> 45:46.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And this is
also a company
that is not public yet, but when
it goes,

45:46.944 --> 45:52.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if it goes, the valuations are
staggering
-- $70 billion is currently
where it's at.

45:52.283 --> 45:56.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does this call into question
perhaps the temperament
of this individual and whether
he is the right

45:57.021 --> 45:59.590 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
person to run such a big global
company?

45:59.624 --> 46:01.525 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE ISAAC: Yes, I think that's
right.

46:01.559 --> 46:07.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Almost a $70 billion valuation,
I think investors,
as well as employees, are
wondering, we had

46:07.064 --> 46:10.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this CEO who got us through the
really tough
early phases.

46:10.668 --> 46:16.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Can this person lead us through
an IPO, where
people really want a more even
keel?

46:16.073 --> 46:19.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think everyone is still
asking that
question, but it's not really
clear at this

46:19.043 --> 46:20.811 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
point.

46:20.845 --> 46:24.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This is in the
wake of the
revelations of a woman who left
the company,

46:24.582 --> 46:27.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and she had this -- part of this
to say in
her blog.

46:27.051 --> 46:33.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"It became obvious that both
H.R. and management
had been lying about this being
his first

46:33.391 --> 46:35.092 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
offense, and it certainly wasn't
his last.

46:35.126 --> 46:38.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The situation was escalated as
far up the
chain as it could be escalated,
and still

46:38.696 --> 46:39.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
nothing was done."

46:39.730 --> 46:41.499 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She's not talking about Travis.

46:41.532 --> 46:45.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She's talking about one of her
managers who
she contends was harassing to
her, and now

46:45.603 --> 46:47.471 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
there's a large investigation.

46:47.505 --> 46:49.507 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is a big deal for the
company.

46:49.540 --> 46:53.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE ISAAC: Yes, this is -- you
know, this
is core to how the culture
operates.

46:53.210 --> 46:58.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, it's very -- to take
it from Facebook,
move fast and break things.

46:58.082 --> 47:02.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, at some point, you have to
sort of clean
things up on the inside and
change, especially

47:02.486 --> 47:03.721 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
if you want to go public.

47:03.754 --> 47:06.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think they're really
facing that question
right now.

47:06.557 --> 47:09.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just a question of, can you
do it and
how long will it take?

47:09.427 --> 47:11.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For a little
while, there
was -- and there might still be
continuing

47:11.929 --> 47:13.364 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
-- a delete Uber campaign.

47:13.397 --> 47:15.099 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Did that have an impact on their
business?

47:15.132 --> 47:16.867 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MIKE ISAAC: Yes, it did.

47:16.901 --> 47:20.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was -- I would say it's not a
material
financial impact, but I have
spoken to a number

47:20.404 --> 47:23.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of people who were watching that
go down inside.

47:23.307 --> 47:27.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, you know, there were
hundreds of thousands
of people that deleted their
Uber accounts

47:27.411 --> 47:31.248 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
entirely, and probably hundreds
of thousands
more that just deleted the app.

47:31.282 --> 47:34.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it worried Uber, and they
definitely tried
to curb it pretty quickly.

47:34.952 --> 47:38.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Mike Isaac of
The New York Times, thanks so
much.

47:38.723 --> 47:47.665 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE ISAAC: Thanks for having
me.

47:47.698 --> 47:54.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now to our
Leading edge
segment for this week: a
potential return

47:54.338 --> 47:56.107 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to the moon.

47:56.140 --> 47:59.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Near the end of his address last
night, the
president made a reference to
space travel,

47:59.610 --> 48:05.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
saying -- quote -- "American
footprints on
distant worlds are not too big a
dream."

48:05.149 --> 48:06.984 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was only a line.

48:07.017 --> 48:11.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But whenever a president speaks
on the subject,
the space community is closely
trying to read

48:11.555 --> 48:13.357 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the tea leaves.

48:13.390 --> 48:17.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The sentence leaves a lot to
interpretation,
but all signs seem to indicate
there is renewed

48:17.795 --> 48:24.368 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
focus inside the Trump
administration, NASA
and the private sector on travel
to the moon,

48:24.401 --> 48:26.070 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
sooner than you might think.

48:26.103 --> 48:29.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our science correspondent, Miles
O'Brien,
is here.

48:29.106 --> 48:31.575 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, Miles, why the moon after
all these years?

48:31.609 --> 48:35.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Aside from the
"because it's
there" answer, it's actually a
good destination

48:35.913 --> 48:39.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to go and learn about living and
working on
an encampment in space.

48:39.650 --> 48:42.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, we went to the moon 50
years ago
now.

48:42.720 --> 48:46.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We left some footprints and
flags behind,
but we didn't really learn how
to live there

48:46.524 --> 48:48.325 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on a sustained basis.

48:48.359 --> 48:51.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, while NASA would still like
to go to Mars,
there's a lot of things you can
learn about

48:51.929 --> 48:53.964 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by setting up an encampment on
the moon.

48:53.998 --> 48:58.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we have learned in the past
50 years there's
a lot of water ice on the moon.

48:58.636 --> 48:59.570 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What is water?

48:59.603 --> 49:00.571 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Hydrogen and oxygen.

49:00.604 --> 49:01.772 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is rocket fuel?

49:01.806 --> 49:03.641 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Hydrogen and oxygen.

49:03.674 --> 49:09.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So you can learn a lot about how
to create
rocket fuel on location and
perhaps push deeper

49:09.113 --> 49:10.848 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
into space.

49:10.881 --> 49:12.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So this didn't
just spring
up as an idea because they
couldn't think

49:12.583 --> 49:13.617 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of anything else?

49:13.651 --> 49:15.286 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, there was
one other factor.

49:15.319 --> 49:19.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There was a mission planned at
the end of
'18 for the Space Launch System,
which is

49:19.690 --> 49:23.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the next heavy lift that NASA is
working -- heavy
lift rocket.

49:23.294 --> 49:26.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One piece of it wasn't going to
be ready,
built by the Europeans, a
service module.

49:26.864 --> 49:31.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so NASA was faced with the
possibility
of delaying that mission, an
unmanned mission,

49:31.235 --> 49:35.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
even later, or maybe doing
something like
we did with Apollo 8, something
bold.

49:35.539 --> 49:38.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the case of Apollo 8, the
lunar module
wasn't ready.

49:38.275 --> 49:40.311 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we decided to go around the
moon.

49:40.344 --> 49:45.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In this case, they're thinking
about putting
astronauts on this flight maybe
early '19,

49:45.516 --> 49:47.785 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and send them around the moon
Apollo 8-style.

49:47.818 --> 49:49.787 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, a lot of things have lined
up.

49:49.820 --> 49:53.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, all of a sudden, there is
wide agreement
in the space community, this
might be the

49:53.891 --> 49:55.759 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
next step.

49:55.793 --> 49:59.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you were
telling me, Miles,
there's a private sector piece
in all of this,

49:59.230 --> 50:04.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Elon Musk announcing just the
other day that
two individuals, I guess, with
some extra

50:04.668 --> 50:05.636 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
spending money...

50:05.669 --> 50:06.637 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: To say the least.

50:06.670 --> 50:08.439 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

50:08.472 --> 50:09.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: ... have told him
they want
to go around the moon and come
back to Earth.

50:09.306 --> 50:10.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes.

50:10.307 --> 50:11.375 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He got a lot of attention for
that.

50:11.408 --> 50:14.011 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He doesn't have a rocket to do
it yet.

50:14.044 --> 50:15.846 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's just a design right now.

50:15.880 --> 50:19.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's called the Falcon Heavy,
which would
have almost the thrust of the
mighty Saturn

50:20.017 --> 50:21.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
5 of Apollo days.

50:22.019 --> 50:24.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It will fly for the first time,
he hopes,
by the summer.

50:24.889 --> 50:29.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So saying there are going to be
paying passengers
on there by '18 is optimistic,
for sure.

50:29.226 --> 50:31.161 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we will watch that with
skepticism.

50:31.195 --> 50:35.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But to the extent that the
private sector
and the government space
enterprise sort of

50:35.666 --> 50:39.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
push each other toward this
destination, a
lot of space people are pretty
excited about

50:39.970 --> 50:41.739 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

50:41.772 --> 50:45.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, remind us,
Miles, why
was the moon -- it was on the
agenda at NASA

50:45.709 --> 50:47.211 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for a while, but it came off.

50:47.244 --> 50:48.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What was that all about?

50:48.245 --> 50:49.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Politics.

50:49.346 --> 50:52.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of course, we lost the shuttle
Columbia in
'03.

50:52.216 --> 50:55.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Bush at the time
canceled the shuttle
program and said, let's go back
to the moon,

50:55.219 --> 50:57.087 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a program called Constellation.

50:57.121 --> 50:59.056 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That got some traction.

50:59.089 --> 51:01.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, of course, President
Obama came
in and said, we're not going to
the moon.

51:01.959 --> 51:03.160 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We're going to Mars.

51:03.193 --> 51:04.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he wouldn't let anybody talk
about going
to the moon.

51:05.029 --> 51:08.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were a lot of people who
said, you know,
we should try the moon first
before we move

51:08.432 --> 51:12.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
onto Mars, but that got shelved
during the
Obama administration.

51:12.236 --> 51:15.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Politics now is different,
obviously, with
the Trump administration there.

51:15.439 --> 51:19.543 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I'm told the Trump
administration would
really like to have U.S.
astronauts taking

51:19.576 --> 51:23.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
off from a U.S. spaceport some
time in its
first term.

51:23.347 --> 51:28.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so this idea of turning that
unmanned
Space Launch System flight into
a crewed mission

51:28.953 --> 51:30.354 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is gaining a lot of traction.

51:30.387 --> 51:32.523 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, finally,
Miles, there
is this question of money.

51:32.556 --> 51:35.225 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It costs money to go into space.

51:35.259 --> 51:40.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a president who has
talked about cutting
back domestic discretionary
spending.

51:40.698 --> 51:41.665 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Where's the money going to come
from?

51:41.699 --> 51:42.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: You know, it's
interesting.

51:42.866 --> 51:44.835 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have to look at the entire
space enterprise
here.

51:44.868 --> 51:49.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NASA's budget is a little more
than $19 billion,
but if you look at the budget
for the military

51:49.139 --> 51:51.442 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
side of space, it's about $40
billion.

51:51.475 --> 51:55.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what if they reconsider this
idea of a
space council, which they're
doing, headed

51:55.779 --> 52:01.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by the vice president, and they
start looking
at ways to carve out and
eliminate some of

52:01.151 --> 52:04.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the redundancies between the
military and
the civilian side?

52:04.355 --> 52:09.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There may be some ways, even
with NASA cuts,
that they can borrow from each
other, feed

52:09.193 --> 52:14.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
each other technology, as it
were, military
and civilian, which could be a
bit of a force

52:14.064 --> 52:16.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
multiplier and could make it
still possible.

52:16.266 --> 52:19.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Interesting,
because the president
has talked about spending a lot
more money

52:19.570 --> 52:20.537 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on defense.

52:20.571 --> 52:21.538 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Exactly.

52:21.572 --> 52:23.073 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, that money might ultimately
help NASA.

52:23.107 --> 52:26.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Miles O'Brien,
taking us to
the moon and back, thank you.

52:26.777 --> 52:28.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: To the moon,
Alice.

52:28.112 --> 52:29.079 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

52:29.113 --> 52:30.414 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank you.

52:30.447 --> 52:37.021 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: You're welcome.

52:37.054 --> 52:44.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: On the "NewsHour"
online right
now: Aboriginal Australian art
is the oldest

52:44.595 --> 52:49.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
continuous art tradition in the
world, stretching
back more than 40,000 years.

52:49.166 --> 52:55.305 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Now, due to a group of
passionate collectors
and curators, Aboriginal
Australian art shows

